{
  "texts": [
    "Molecular graphs, for instance, encode molecular topology (atoms and bonds) and properties (atom properties and/or coordinates, and bond properties) in a permutation-invariant manner.",
    "In other words, every molecule (given a set of atom and bond properties to capture) maps to a unique molecular graph, rendering a 'SMILES-like' augmentation impossible.",
    "Similarly, molecular descriptors map one-to-one with the molecular representation they are computed from, rendering permutation-based augmentation unfeasible.",
    "A useful, albeit less explored, approach to circumvent this limitation is by considering 3D conformations and performing 'conformer-based augmentation'.",
    "Here, the same molecule is described by several, different 3D conformations, which enables data augmentation with molecular graphs and/or molecular descriptors that capture 3D information [5]."
  ]
}